Mr.

Oh, yeah.

The only ones that really disturbed me

And they were speaking in very politically stable or politically correct statements.
And it was just a position paper.
I detest position papers for commencement addresses.
Do you remember any incidents on the stage at commencement, plus or minus?
Oh, probably.
The most hilarious one was a young man came up the steps on crutches one day, got his diploma, got halfway across the stage, put the crutches under his arm, and ran off the stage.
OK. My last commencement to attend was the last of the spring commencements 20 years ago in 1980.
And the last person to walk across the stage was a young woman in biomedical science named Melanie Zender.
Describe what you recall.
I honestly, Haskell, I did not see it.
Brian told me about it.
As you heard it described by whomever,
That I heard.
That was about two feet from where I was seated next to Governor Hobby.
And as I remember it, when she put her hand out, Dr. Miller says softly, no way I'm going to shake your hand.

She then turned and put out her hand and he said, ma'am, I'm not involved in this argument.
And Don Carter said, ma'am, would you please keep the line moving?

That was not true.
No.

Six weeks later, when Dr. Miller is dismissed,

I don't know what I was doing, but I didn't see it.
All right, how did you get involved in athletic announcing?
I struck up a friendship with Jim Butler in the summer or fall of 1967.
And at that time, his duties were...
He was a student.
He was a student worker for a spec cabin in the athletic department.

Well, then during the basketball season,

No.
Everything I've done in public address work, I've done on my own.
I started doing public address work for football when I was a junior in high school at home.
We had a bandstand that the band played in at the games.
And I had a portable PA system that we put up on that bandstand.
And I stood on the bandstand.
And I did the PA for my high school for two years, junior and senior year, in 1940, fall of 41 and fall of 42.
And then I dabbled around whenever I could.
When I was a student at Iowa State, I spotted the radio stations on all the home games.
The radio stations would come in, and I worked for the athletic department as a spotter, learned to follow players that way.
When I went to Auburn, their high school had never had anybody do their games when I went there.
And so the fall of 63, I did all their high school home games.
And so I just sort of worked into it.
And then I got into track.
And then I got into volleyball.
Kay Don asked me to come and do a volleyball tournament match for her one day.
And so I kept on doing that.
Well, that first day, I did a volleyball match.

I knew what was going on.

You didn't give the play-by-play, I know that.
My concept of public address announcers, and of course that's what got me replaced here in both volleyball and basketball, is simplicity.
And it also created an opportunity for me I wouldn't have had otherwise.
When the Southwest Conference started having basketball tournaments, they usually used an announcer who was at the home place.
They moved it to San Antonio in 1980.
And I said something to Bill Morgan.
I don't know where I happened to see him.
I said, Bill, I'll be happy to do the tournament if you want me to.
I'll come down and do it for you.
He said, gosh, I wish I'd have known that last year.
He said, I'd have had you in Houston.

And so I went to San Antonio in 1980 and did the Southwest Conference Tournament, and then I did the Southwest Conference Tournament in 81 in San Antonio, and I did the Southwest Tournament every year until 1993.

Define what you meant by simplicity.
Who does what in a tournament.

In 1955, I was practicing veterinary medicine in the little town of Ida Grove, Iowa, in northwest Iowa.
One of my clients had a son who was a senior in high school.
And I went out there one morning and he said, Leo's running a track meet and posting this afternoon.
He said, if you can, go see.
So I did.
I took the afternoon off and went up.
He's running in a mile run.
And his dad said, oh, Leo can't go to Iowa State.
He was going to a high school that had 35 students in it.
And they were tenant farmers, and they didn't have anything.
And I said, well, go and see.
